The Telegraph - Calcutta (Kolkata) | Sports | Briefs
                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                             
	Melbourne: Thanks to a horrendous opening round of six-over 78, Shiv Kapur will require a miracle to make the cut at the Australian Masters. Indian-born Swede Daniel Chopra carded two-under 70 to brighten his chance of a top finish in the European Tour event.    
	A 10th tee starter, Shiv completed his first nine at even-par before running into a wretched front nine. By the time he approached the sixth hole, he had dropped five shots and the seventh hole birdie was of little consolation as the Indian had a bogey-bogey finish.        
	Santa Barbara: Tennis great Jimmy Connors has been charged with a misdemeanor for an altercation last week before a college basketball game.    
	Connors was charged in Santa Barbara Superior Court with disrupting University of California Santa Barbara campus activities and refusing to leave a university facility.    
	His business manager, Karen Scott, says a man tried to pick a fight with Connors and his son before Fridays game and police asked him to leave. Scott says Connors was arrested after he said he wanted to wait for his son to finish watching the game.        
	 Manacor: World No. 1 Rafael Nadal has said it shows a lack of respect when people write off Roger Federer. He has proven he is a winner. At the US Open he won and silenced many people who said he was finished, a Spanish daily said. It shows a lack of respect when they say things like that.         
	Calcutta: Bengal won two golds and one silver medal at the sub-junior National Table Tennis Championship in Vijaywada, says A Staff Reporter. In cadet boys Bengal beat North Bengal 3-1, and in sub-junior girls Bengal got past Maharashtra 3-2.          
	Calcutta: Sourav Ganguly will be felicitated by the CAB on January 18, says A Staff Reporter. This was finalised at the CAB working committee meeting on Thursday.     
	A three-member fact finding panel, consisting of Justice Umesh Banerjee, Justice Dilip Bose and Prasanta Mullick, chartered accountant and former senior partner of PricewaterhouseCoopers, -was formed to look into the expenses during the inaugural Indian Premier League.          
	Centurion: South Africa will play an extra warm-up match in Australia following the postponement of the inaugural Twenty20 Champions League in India which was due to start next week.         
	New Delhi: Virender Sehwag returned to lead the Delhi team as the selectors picked a 15-member squad for the Ranji Trophy match against Orissa, scheduled from November 29 here.
                                                                                                                                                                     
